## Conversation
PR1 of the stack from "do that as a stack of PRs" (page-cache leak fix).
Originally implemented as a per-instance OrderedDict LRU. The user then left a
Conductor review comment on _fetch_page: "is this the best way? What if we
instead implemented as a helper func that used lru_cache?" I evaluated, the
user chose the helper, and this commit was amended (gt modify) to the
helper+lru_cache form.

## Actions
- Built a runnable demo (.context/pagecache_demo.py, gitignored) comparing 4
  strategies for leak/cycle behavior via weakref-after-del:
    method lru_cache (OLD)   freed_on_refcount=False freed_after_gc=False  LEAK
    helper lru_cache         freed_on_refcount=True  freed_after_gc=True   clean
    bound-method lru_cache   freed_on_refcount=False freed_after_gc=True   cyclic
    OrderedDict (PR1 v1)     freed_on_refcount=True  freed_after_gc=True   clean
- Consulted Codex (threadId 019ea725-...): recommended KEEPING OrderedDict
  because its leak-safety is structural, whereas the helper's safety depends on
  the invariant 'fetch_func never closes over the iterator' and B019 won't
  catch a regression. User chose the helper anyway (explicit override; prefers
  stdlib cache machinery). Complied.
- Implemented _make_page_fetcher(fetch_func, page_size, max_cached_pages): a
  free function returning an lru_cache-wrapped closure. __init__ assigns
  self._fetch_page = _make_page_fetcher(...). Removed the _fetch_page method
  and the OrderedDict import; restored functools.lru_cache import.
- ruff clean; 5 unit tests pass (incl. test_paginated_iterator_released_when_
  unreferenced, the weakref leak regression -- passes because the closure does
  not capture self).

